HEADWORD: Prehensile
<hw>Pre*hen"sile</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>prehensus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>prehendere</ets> to lay hold of,
seize; <ets>pre-</ets> (equiv. to <ets>prae</ets> before) +
<ets>hendere</ets> (in comp.), akin to E. <ets>get</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>pr⟦eacute⟧hensile</ets>. See <er>Get</er>, and cf. <er>Prison</er>,
<er>Prize</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>Adapted to seize or grasp;
seizing; grasping; <as>as, the <ex>prehensile</ex> tail of a
monkey</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prehension</ent>⟦br⟧
